WEBVTT

1
00:01:05.170 --> 00:01:06.569
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

2
00:01:08.330 --> 00:01:10.127
(ANIMALS CALLING)

3
00:01:13.170 --> 00:01:15.161
(ELEPHANTS TRUMPETING)

4
00:01:35.250 --> 00:01:36.444
(BIRDS CALLING)

5
00:01:42.770 --> 00:01:43.919
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

6
00:01:45.930 --> 00:01:47.946
ANTONINA: Hello, Jerzyk.
JERZYK: Good morning, Miss.


7
00:01:47.970 --> 00:01:49.289
It's a beautiful day.

8
00:01:58.970 --> 00:02:01.040
Good morning.

9
00:02:01.130 --> 00:02:03.405
Hello. Welcome.
MAN: Good morning.


10
00:02:04.890 --> 00:02:06.448
Good morning.
Enjoy yourselves today.


11
00:02:07.210 --> 00:02:08.210
Good morning.

12
00:02:13.010 --> 00:02:14.489
Good morning.

13
00:02:15.810 --> 00:02:17.323
Good morning.
ANTONINA: Good morning.


14
00:02:24.170 --> 00:02:26.968
Come along, Adam.
Time for morning rounds.


15
00:02:29.690 --> 00:02:31.442
(GRUNTING)

16
00:02:32.810 --> 00:02:34.528
(LOW GROWLING)

17
00:02:44.490 --> 00:02:46.720
(LOW GROWLING)
ANTONINA: Hello, my loves.


18
00:02:48.970 --> 00:02:50.119
Good morning, sweetheart.

19
00:02:50.850 --> 00:02:52.488
(GROWLING)

20
00:02:53.170 --> 00:02:54.170
(TIGER ROARS)

21
00:02:56.410 --> 00:02:57.410
Good morning.

22
00:03:02.530 --> 00:03:03.679
(ADAM GRUNTING)

23
00:03:09.490 --> 00:03:11.162
(MONKEYS CHATTERING)

24
00:03:20.970 --> 00:03:22.039
(SPEAKING POLISH)

25
00:03:25.690 --> 00:03:26.725
(POLAR BEAR GRUNTING)

26
00:03:30.730 --> 00:03:32.083
(ELEPHANT TRUMPETING)

27
00:03:34.290 --> 00:03:35.723
How's our girl today?

28
00:03:35.810 --> 00:03:37.163
No problems today, Miss.

29
00:03:40.770 --> 00:03:43.887
Hello, old Kasia.

30
00:03:43.970 --> 00:03:47.167
Yes. Tembo.

31
00:03:47.250 --> 00:03:49.241
What a beautiful girl
you are.


32
00:04:00.330 --> 00:04:01.843
(CHILDREN CHATTERING)

33
00:04:04.690 --> 00:04:05.725
(YELPS)

34
00:04:06.850 --> 00:04:08.078
(SCREECHING)

35
00:04:08.970 --> 00:04:11.040
(LOW GRUNTING)
Good morning.


36
00:04:25.970 --> 00:04:28.609
Good morning, darling.
Good morning, Punia.


37
00:04:30.850 --> 00:04:31.919
Have you come to help me?

38
00:05:09.930 --> 00:05:12.205
LUTZ HECK: The torchlight
was flaring in front of me.


39
00:05:12.290 --> 00:05:14.929
Behind me, I could hear the
breathing of a maddened creature.


40
00:05:15.010 --> 00:05:17.604
It was midnight,
black as coal.


41
00:05:18.290 --> 00:05:20.246
I couldn't see
my hand in front of me,


42
00:05:20.330 --> 00:05:22.525
but I could feel
her breath on my neck.


43
00:05:22.610 --> 00:05:24.965
Hot and thick.

44
00:05:25.050 --> 00:05:27.769
I had interfered,
and she was angry with me.


45
00:05:28.650 --> 00:05:30.322
She took two steps.

46
00:05:32.130 --> 00:05:34.405
I thought
it was the end of me.


47
00:05:34.490 --> 00:05:38.085
I took my rifle,
raised it,


48
00:05:38.170 --> 00:05:39.810
and that's when she charged.
(STOMPS FOOT)


49
00:05:39.890 --> 00:05:40.890
(PEOPLE GASPING)

50
00:05:43.930 --> 00:05:46.888
There was nothing I could do,
I had to shoot her.


51
00:05:48.130 --> 00:05:50.325
It was the picture
of perfection.


52
00:05:50.410 --> 00:05:51.889
An exquisite creature.

53
00:05:52.970 --> 00:05:54.847
A great desecration
for me.


54
00:05:55.050 --> 00:05:58.645
But I have to say,
her cubs did survive.


55
00:05:59.210 --> 00:06:03.681
They thrived, and have grown to a
proud maturity in my zoo. Cheers.


56
00:06:04.330 --> 00:06:07.322
Herr Heck has taken over the
Berlin Zoo from his father.


57
00:06:07.570 --> 00:06:09.288
And his brother
runs the Munich Zoo.


58
00:06:09.370 --> 00:06:11.122
Would you like a canapé,
Herr Heck?


59
00:06:11.210 --> 00:06:13.041
It looks delicious,
but no. Thank you.


60
00:06:13.130 --> 00:06:15.803
This is Magda Gross, the sculptress.
Perhaps you know of her.


61
00:06:15.890 --> 00:06:16.890
Indeed, yes.

62
00:06:16.930 --> 00:06:18.761
She also made this...
Oh!


63
00:06:20.210 --> 00:06:21.210
Excuse me.

64
00:06:22.010 --> 00:06:24.205
WANDA: And what do you do
with yourself, my dear,


65
00:06:24.290 --> 00:06:26.130
while your husband is
playing with his monkeys?


66
00:06:26.690 --> 00:06:28.203
(SNICKERING)

67
00:06:28.330 --> 00:06:29.558
I help him.

68
00:06:29.770 --> 00:06:31.522
Oh, isn't that sweet.

69
00:06:31.610 --> 00:06:33.646
Sweetness is the least of it.

70
00:06:33.730 --> 00:06:35.925
Antonina's a magician.

71
00:06:36.010 --> 00:06:39.639
Thank you. I'll take it.

72
00:06:39.730 --> 00:06:42.005
We met five or six years ago,
didn't we, Frau Zabinska?


73
00:06:42.090 --> 00:06:43.090
Mmm.

74
00:06:43.170 --> 00:06:44.649
I think you've
changed your hair.


75
00:06:44.730 --> 00:06:45.799
Yes.

76
00:06:45.930 --> 00:06:47.363
You've only grown
more beautiful


77
00:06:47.450 --> 00:06:48.706
in these past years,
I have to say.


78
00:06:48.730 --> 00:06:51.085
The look of a stray
barn cat, if you ask me.


79
00:06:51.930 --> 00:06:55.639
Did you know that barn cats have the
keenest sense in all of nature?


80
00:06:55.730 --> 00:06:58.483
More astute and fine than any
human being I hope to meet.


81
00:07:01.290 --> 00:07:03.850
Do you play the piano,
Frau Zabinska?


82
00:07:03.930 --> 00:07:05.329
A little.

83
00:07:05.450 --> 00:07:06.850
Why don't you play
something for us?


84
00:07:07.690 --> 00:07:09.521
I think it's
the perfect time


85
00:07:09.610 --> 00:07:12.283
to soothe the savage
beast and all that.


86
00:07:17.290 --> 00:07:19.008
Maybe she should play
a German waltz.


87
00:07:19.490 --> 00:07:21.879
We may all be learning the
goose-step within a year.


88
00:07:22.050 --> 00:07:24.041
Stefan, please.
STEFAN: Isn't that so, Herr Heck?


89
00:07:24.130 --> 00:07:25.358
JAN: Not now, please, Stefan.

90
00:07:25.610 --> 00:07:28.761
Well, Hitler wants Poland.

91
00:07:28.890 --> 00:07:30.528
It's what everyone's saying.

92
00:07:30.610 --> 00:07:33.522
I wouldn't know anything about it,
I assure you.


93
00:07:33.610 --> 00:07:36.078
I'm a zoologist,
not a politician.


94
00:07:37.010 --> 00:07:38.489
(ANTONINA PLAYING PIANO)

95
00:07:48.570 --> 00:07:49.570
(DOOR OPENS)

96
00:07:51.050 --> 00:07:53.803
Mama, Jerzyk needs you!
It's Kasia.


97
00:07:54.690 --> 00:07:56.123
Excuse me, everyone.

98
00:07:58.490 --> 00:08:00.481
Be quiet, don't startle her.
(KASIA TRUMPETING)


99
00:08:08.650 --> 00:08:12.325
Here, stay here.
Hold the light steady for me.


100
00:08:21.850 --> 00:08:23.841
JERZYK:
She's not breathing.


101
00:08:27.490 --> 00:08:30.004
I'm here, Kasia.

102
00:08:30.090 --> 00:08:32.479
I'm here.

103
00:08:32.770 --> 00:08:33.770
Hello, Tembo.

104
00:08:35.890 --> 00:08:37.039
Hello, Tembo.

105
00:08:37.130 --> 00:08:40.440
I can bring you overalls, Miss, please.
I can find other men.


106
00:08:40.890 --> 00:08:42.881
ANTONINA: There's no time.
She's suffocating.


107
00:08:43.370 --> 00:08:45.486
Let me help you, Kasia.

108
00:08:45.570 --> 00:08:48.038
Please, let me help you,
my darling.


109
00:08:48.410 --> 00:08:50.287
Let me help you,
sweetheart.


110
00:08:50.370 --> 00:08:52.167
JERZYK: I have no rifle,
Miss, please!


111
00:08:52.410 --> 00:08:53.604
Hush! Enough now!

112
00:08:57.290 --> 00:08:58.405
Please.

113
00:09:00.410 --> 00:09:01.684
Oh, she's blocked!

114
00:09:08.330 --> 00:09:10.207
No, please, let me do this.

115
00:09:10.850 --> 00:09:13.523
I'm trying, Kasia.
I'm trying, my darling.


116
00:09:16.290 --> 00:09:17.290
(GRUNTS)

117
00:09:22.450 --> 00:09:24.406
(GROWLING)

118
00:09:28.170 --> 00:09:29.398
Wait, wait, wait.

119
00:09:29.490 --> 00:09:31.186
You should go. You can go.
Why isn't that man armed?


120
00:09:31.210 --> 00:09:33.565
(TRUMPETING)

121
00:09:35.410 --> 00:09:36.923
JERZYK: Whoa, Tembo.

122
00:09:37.010 --> 00:09:38.330
LUTZ HECK: What's his name?
Tembo.


123
00:09:38.930 --> 00:09:42.081
Tembo! Tembo.
Good. Good, good, good.


124
00:09:42.250 --> 00:09:43.808
(GRUNTING)

125
00:09:43.890 --> 00:09:45.323
(PANTING)

126
00:09:45.410 --> 00:09:47.765
We're losing her!
Jerzyk, help me!


127
00:09:52.090 --> 00:09:53.090
(GRUNTS)

128
00:09:53.330 --> 00:09:55.525
Push, Jerzyk!

129
00:09:55.610 --> 00:09:56.804
Push! (SOBS)

130
00:09:58.730 --> 00:10:00.083
Go. Go, go, go.

131
00:10:06.210 --> 00:10:07.210
ANTONINA: Oh!

132
00:10:10.490 --> 00:10:11.490
(GASPING)

133
00:10:11.570 --> 00:10:13.640
Oh, she's breathing!
(SOBBING AND LAUGHING)


134
00:10:14.730 --> 00:10:16.641
Oh! She's breathing!

135
00:10:21.770 --> 00:10:23.169
You beauty!

136
00:10:26.330 --> 00:10:28.605
She's beautiful!

137
00:10:30.050 --> 00:10:32.564
Amazing! Amazing!

138
00:10:34.130 --> 00:10:35.927
(CHUCKLES)

139
00:10:36.010 --> 00:10:38.160
That was hard work,
wasn't it?


140
00:10:38.810 --> 00:10:40.163
(LAUGHING)

141
00:10:42.130 --> 00:10:46.203
It's all right.
It's all right, sweetheart.


142
00:10:54.730 --> 00:10:55.730
(LAUGHS)

143
00:11:04.850 --> 00:11:06.408
You are a, um...

144
00:11:08.250 --> 00:11:12.687
You are a wonder, Punia.
You are Eve in her garden.


145
00:11:12.850 --> 00:11:13.850
(ANTONINA CHUCKLES)

146
00:11:19.210 --> 00:11:20.848
(BABY ELEPHANT COOS)

147
00:11:27.490 --> 00:11:28.764
It's late. Let's go home.

148
00:11:31.210 --> 00:11:33.087
(BELL TOLLING)

149
00:11:37.410 --> 00:11:39.321
JERZYK: Good morning.
Good morning.


150
00:11:39.410 --> 00:11:41.401
Let's go! We're going.

151
00:11:53.330 --> 00:11:56.959
Mama, what are those men doing?
They look like mules.


152
00:12:06.490 --> 00:12:08.720
ANTONINA: We were on
Nalewki Street today.


153
00:12:09.850 --> 00:12:13.320
They're working the Jews
like pack animals now.


154
00:12:16.490 --> 00:12:20.244
I think you should take Rys
out of Warsaw tomorrow.


155
00:12:23.090 --> 00:12:24.808
But where will we go?

156
00:12:25.570 --> 00:12:29.279
You could stay with
my cousins in Zalesie.


157
00:12:29.370 --> 00:12:31.122
Things are too
uncertain here.


158
00:12:31.210 --> 00:12:35.123
We should get Rys out of
the city while we can.


159
00:12:35.210 --> 00:12:38.361
But school's
about to start.


160
00:12:38.490 --> 00:12:42.199
Oh, he's so excited, Jan,
with his new pencils, and his shoes...


161
00:12:42.290 --> 00:12:46.408
You're not listening to me.
I'm trying to tell you something.


162
00:12:48.210 --> 00:12:50.678
It's feeling very dangerous
to me right now.


163
00:12:55.330 --> 00:12:58.003
What about you?

164
00:12:58.090 --> 00:13:00.445
I have to stay
for the animals,


165
00:13:00.530 --> 00:13:02.839
but I'll come
as soon as I can.


166
00:13:18.010 --> 00:13:22.049
Punia, Hitler and Stalin
have signed a pact.


167
00:13:22.130 --> 00:13:23.802
Only Poland
sits in the middle.


168
00:13:24.410 --> 00:13:27.447
People are leaving.

169
00:13:27.530 --> 00:13:29.725
We could stay in
Zalesie for a little while,


170
00:13:29.810 --> 00:13:33.598
but if war comes, we have to
find a way out of the country.


171
00:13:33.690 --> 00:13:35.408
I don't want to run away.

172
00:13:35.490 --> 00:13:39.642
I don't want to carry Rys from place
to place, like a frightened cat.


173
00:13:42.330 --> 00:13:44.719
This is his home.

174
00:13:46.050 --> 00:13:49.929
I'm sorry, Punia.
Come back to me, come here.


175
00:13:50.010 --> 00:13:53.002
People always want to run when
they don't know what's coming.


176
00:13:53.090 --> 00:13:57.242
It's their first instinct,
always to run.


177
00:13:57.330 --> 00:14:00.959
Come.
It's not good for a child.


178
00:14:01.050 --> 00:14:04.645
It's not good, Jan,
I'm telling you.


179
00:14:04.730 --> 00:14:07.961
I don't want Rys
to live that way.


180
00:14:08.890 --> 00:14:09.890
(SIGHS)

181
00:14:12.010 --> 00:14:14.683
Please,
I want to stay here.


182
00:14:16.170 --> 00:14:17.364
In Warsaw.

183
00:14:22.090 --> 00:14:23.159
All right.

184
00:14:41.690 --> 00:14:43.442
(BELL TOLLING)

185
00:14:46.290 --> 00:14:47.723
(AIRPLANES PASSING OVERHEAD)

186
00:14:53.810 --> 00:14:56.529
Rys? Rys!

187
00:15:00.170 --> 00:15:01.170
(PANTING)

188
00:15:02.810 --> 00:15:04.641
Look at all the planes!

189
00:15:05.730 --> 00:15:07.448
Let's go inside.

190
00:15:07.570 --> 00:15:08.570
(SCREAMS)

191
00:15:14.130 --> 00:15:15.529
(ELEPHANTS TRUMPETING)

192
00:15:15.770 --> 00:15:17.522
(ROARING)

193
00:15:18.450 --> 00:15:19.929
(BOMBS EXPLODING)

194
00:15:21.610 --> 00:15:24.124
(GROWLING)

195
00:15:24.370 --> 00:15:26.281
(BELLOWING)

196
00:15:26.690 --> 00:15:27.759
(SCREECHING)

197
00:15:31.930 --> 00:15:32.930
(EXPLOSIONS CONTINUE)

198
00:15:33.370 --> 00:15:35.247
RYS: But where's Papa?
He's in Plonsk.


199
00:15:35.450 --> 00:15:37.361
We'll meet him in Zalesie.

200
00:15:37.450 --> 00:15:38.963
RYS: What about Pancho?
(PANTING)


201
00:15:39.290 --> 00:15:41.281
Quick, pack your things!

202
00:15:41.370 --> 00:15:43.600
No, Rys, leave him!
No, I don't want to.


203
00:15:43.690 --> 00:15:44.946
We'll open the doors.
He's scared.


204
00:15:44.970 --> 00:15:47.962
He'll run somewhere safe.
Let's go!


205
00:15:50.050 --> 00:15:51.449
(CHITTERING)

206
00:15:55.490 --> 00:15:56.809
(WHINNYING)

207
00:15:56.890 --> 00:15:58.164
Mama!

208
00:16:01.170 --> 00:16:04.321
MAN: (ON LOUDSPEAKER)
Evacuate the zoo immediately!


209
00:16:04.410 --> 00:16:05.410
(SIRENS BLARING)

210
00:16:05.530 --> 00:16:08.806
This is the Polish Army.
Wild animals are loose.


211
00:16:09.050 --> 00:16:12.042
Emergency! Emergency!

212
00:16:12.130 --> 00:16:14.086
Evacuate now!

213
00:16:14.410 --> 00:16:17.447
Take the boy,
Miss, please! Go, go!


214
00:16:17.530 --> 00:16:19.486
(CAMELS GRUNTING)
(PANTING)


215
00:16:19.570 --> 00:16:21.003
(ELEPHANTS TRUMPETING)

216
00:16:25.370 --> 00:16:27.964
No! Don't shoot him,
don't shoot him!


217
00:16:28.050 --> 00:16:29.085
No!
(GUNS FIRING)


218
00:16:29.170 --> 00:16:31.286
RYS: No, Mama!

219
00:16:31.370 --> 00:16:33.122
(RYS SOBBING)

220
00:16:39.490 --> 00:16:41.003
(WHINNYING)

221
00:17:15.090 --> 00:17:16.090
(GRUNTING)

222
00:17:17.090 --> 00:17:18.887
(PEOPLE CLAMORING)

223
00:17:21.250 --> 00:17:23.047
(AIRPLANES PASSING OVERHEAD)

224
00:17:27.010 --> 00:17:28.887
(SIREN WAILING)

225
00:17:38.610 --> 00:17:41.249
Excuse me, where is
the train to Zalesie?


226
00:17:44.570 --> 00:17:46.959
MAN: (ON PA)
No trains running today!


227
00:17:47.090 --> 00:17:52.244
No trains today!
Leave the station immediately.


228
00:18:00.570 --> 00:18:02.925
(MAN SPEAKING POLISH)

229
00:18:09.410 --> 00:18:10.410
Papa!

230
00:18:11.770 --> 00:18:13.169
Antonina!

231
00:18:13.250 --> 00:18:14.478
Rys, Rys,
come, come, come.


232
00:18:14.570 --> 00:18:15.719
Papa!

233
00:18:16.490 --> 00:18:17.718
(ALL PANTING)

234
00:18:17.810 --> 00:18:18.845
(KISSING)

235
00:18:18.930 --> 00:18:19.999
I thought you were lost.

236
00:18:21.010 --> 00:18:22.489
Come, come. Come.

237
00:18:22.570 --> 00:18:23.706
ANTONINA: I can't believe
you found us.


238
00:18:23.730 --> 00:18:25.641
Let's go home.

239
00:18:49.130 --> 00:18:52.327
Hey. Maybe you'd
like to fly. Come.


240
00:18:58.930 --> 00:19:00.602
(RYS MIMICKING
AIRPLANE SOUNDS)


241
00:19:04.330 --> 00:19:05.729
Come, Punia.

242
00:20:05.290 --> 00:20:06.290
Pancho!

243
00:20:17.730 --> 00:20:20.802
Pancho, I'm here.

244
00:20:20.890 --> 00:20:22.084
It's all right.

245
00:20:32.250 --> 00:20:34.525
He's all right, Mama.

246
00:20:37.690 --> 00:20:39.203
(FLIES BUZZING)

247
00:20:49.930 --> 00:20:51.409
(BIRD SQUAWKING)

248
00:21:10.090 --> 00:21:14.641
Oh, you poor things.
You must have been so scared.


249
00:21:17.210 --> 00:21:18.609
(RADIO STATIC)

250
00:21:20.370 --> 00:21:21.946
GENERAL ROMMEL: (ON RADIO)
The German government


251
00:21:21.970 --> 00:21:23.847
has taken charge
of the Polish people.


252
00:21:24.690 --> 00:21:27.363
We rely on the
population of Warsaw


253
00:21:27.450 --> 00:21:30.283
to accept the entry
of German forces


254
00:21:30.370 --> 00:21:33.840
quietly, honorably,
and calmly.


255
00:21:34.050 --> 00:21:35.403
They're here, Mama.

256
00:21:35.570 --> 00:21:37.090
(GENERAL ROMMEL
CONTINUES IN GERMAN)


257
00:21:38.930 --> 00:21:40.966
(SOLDIERS SHOUTING IN GERMAN)

258
00:21:59.370 --> 00:22:00.883
Let's go.

259
00:22:05.650 --> 00:22:08.164
JAN: They're using
our enclosures as an armory.


260
00:22:09.250 --> 00:22:12.560
The country's
completely overrun.


261
00:22:12.690 --> 00:22:13.890
I was raised
with these people.


262
00:22:15.850 --> 00:22:17.488
Jews, Gentiles.

263
00:22:17.890 --> 00:22:20.723
It didn't matter to my family.
It never mattered to me.


264
00:22:25.850 --> 00:22:27.124
(GRUNTING)

265
00:22:32.410 --> 00:22:34.207
(CONVERSING IN GERMAN)

266
00:22:35.370 --> 00:22:36.370
(SNICKERING)

267
00:22:40.050 --> 00:22:41.688
Guten Tag,
meine Herren.


268
00:22:44.930 --> 00:22:45.999
(CLEARS THROAT)

269
00:22:51.730 --> 00:22:53.482
Herr Heck.

270
00:22:53.570 --> 00:22:55.367
Thank you, Jerzyk.

271
00:22:55.450 --> 00:22:56.929
Hello.

272
00:22:57.010 --> 00:22:58.363
It's terrible,
Frau Zabinska.


273
00:22:59.050 --> 00:23:02.884
Yes. It is.

274
00:23:04.970 --> 00:23:07.564
You know, we weren't
expecting you.


275
00:23:07.650 --> 00:23:10.084
I'm so sorry.
My husband's not here, so...


276
00:23:10.610 --> 00:23:11.725
Can we talk?

277
00:23:13.210 --> 00:23:16.202
Yes, of course. Please.

278
00:23:21.650 --> 00:23:23.083
(GRUNTING)

279
00:23:40.090 --> 00:23:44.129
Your zoo is to be liquidated.
I'm sorry to tell you.


280
00:23:47.210 --> 00:23:50.361
I don't understand
what you mean.


281
00:23:51.890 --> 00:23:54.882
For the war effort.

282
00:23:54.970 --> 00:23:57.609
Meat, firewood,

283
00:23:57.770 --> 00:23:59.488
soap...
No.


284
00:24:01.130 --> 00:24:02.130
(SNIFFLES)

285
00:24:05.530 --> 00:24:08.442
(SNIFFLING)
No. It can't be true.


286
00:24:09.450 --> 00:24:10.450
The animals?

287
00:24:12.690 --> 00:24:14.408
All of them?

288
00:24:14.490 --> 00:24:16.446
Another tragedy, I know.

289
00:24:18.890 --> 00:24:23.566
But I see a way out
of this, my friend.


290
00:24:24.450 --> 00:24:26.600
That's why I've come.

291
00:24:26.690 --> 00:24:28.999
But you need to listen to me now.
You need to trust me.


292
00:24:29.090 --> 00:24:31.729
Now, I could take your prize
animals to Germany as a loan.


293
00:24:32.370 --> 00:24:35.407
We'll give them sanctuary.

294
00:24:35.490 --> 00:24:37.242
You know you can
trust my word on this.


295
00:24:37.330 --> 00:24:39.330
And when the war is over,
I can return them to you.


296
00:24:40.130 --> 00:24:44.248
But what if the war
comes to Germany?


297
00:24:44.330 --> 00:24:47.242
A terrible thought, I know,
and a personal nightmare for me,


298
00:24:47.330 --> 00:24:50.561
but I must tell you the
Allied forces are very weak.


299
00:24:50.650 --> 00:24:52.481
I expect this
to be over very soon.


300
00:24:54.010 --> 00:24:56.763
I want to rescue
the best of your breeds.


301
00:24:56.850 --> 00:24:59.444
And I can secure them a future
no matter what might come.


302
00:24:59.530 --> 00:25:01.885
And we can do this together,
Frau Zabinska.


303
00:25:03.170 --> 00:25:06.401
We can save your
animals together.


304
00:25:06.530 --> 00:25:08.088
What do you think?

305
00:25:08.170 --> 00:25:09.489
Yes.

306
00:25:12.370 --> 00:25:14.247
Of course
we must do it.


307
00:25:14.370 --> 00:25:16.930
I'll bring trucks
as soon as I can.


308
00:25:17.010 --> 00:25:19.843
Your animals will be fine.
I give you my word.


309
00:25:24.330 --> 00:25:26.890
I don't know
how to thank you.


310
00:25:29.810 --> 00:25:32.040
It's from one animal lover
to another, hmm?


311
00:25:33.530 --> 00:25:34.645
JAN: What do you mean?

312
00:25:35.450 --> 00:25:37.566
Lutz Heck is taking
all the animals?


313
00:25:37.650 --> 00:25:42.087
No, just the prize stock,
for safekeeping.


314
00:25:42.170 --> 00:25:44.206
Ah, but that's
our stock, Punia.


315
00:25:44.290 --> 00:25:46.565
That's all that's left to
keep the zoo in operation.


316
00:25:47.530 --> 00:25:50.602
Why didn't he wait
to speak to me?


317
00:25:51.930 --> 00:25:54.569
He said
he didn't have time.


318
00:25:57.210 --> 00:25:59.565
Jan, he wants to help.

319
00:26:02.050 --> 00:26:03.881
So, I gave him
our permission.


320
00:26:03.970 --> 00:26:06.803
He doesn't need
our permission, Punia.


321
00:26:06.890 --> 00:26:10.849
Don't you see?
He's Hitler's head zoologist.


322
00:26:10.970 --> 00:26:12.847
Lutz Heck controls our zoo.

323
00:26:18.930 --> 00:26:20.841
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

324
00:26:30.930 --> 00:26:33.524
My God!

325
00:26:33.610 --> 00:26:36.044
Beautiful. Jerzyk, wait.
Wait, please.


326
00:26:36.130 --> 00:26:37.324
(CUBS PURRING)

327
00:26:41.610 --> 00:26:43.328
Stay safe, my beauty.

328
00:26:56.450 --> 00:26:57.450
(LOW GROWLING)

329
00:27:06.490 --> 00:27:08.640
Put him
in Herr Heck's truck.


330
00:27:09.890 --> 00:27:10.959
Come.

331
00:27:13.770 --> 00:27:15.442
Thank you, Jan.

332
00:27:15.970 --> 00:27:17.403
Goodbye, Frau Zabinska.

333
00:27:30.650 --> 00:27:31.878
(CHIRPING)

334
00:27:32.170 --> 00:27:33.603
(GRUNTING)

335
00:27:34.850 --> 00:27:37.489
(PARTY HORNS BLOWING)

336
00:27:41.770 --> 00:27:43.408
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

337
00:27:44.970 --> 00:27:46.306
ANTONINA: "The rich
shoemaker in the town


338
00:27:46.330 --> 00:27:50.369
"took the measure of the
little foot into his own room


339
00:27:50.450 --> 00:27:55.604
"in which stood great glass
cases full of pretty shoes.


340
00:27:56.290 --> 00:28:00.078
"She sat down and made,
well, as well as she could,


341
00:28:00.170 --> 00:28:02.604
"a pair of little..." Ah!

342
00:28:02.690 --> 00:28:06.478
I think Papa's home in time
for New Year's Eve.


343
00:28:06.610 --> 00:28:07.838
(VEHICLE APPROACHING)

344
00:28:08.810 --> 00:28:10.209
(CAR DOORS OPENING)

345
00:28:12.210 --> 00:28:13.529
(ANIMAL WHINNYING)

346
00:28:16.290 --> 00:28:17.290
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

347
00:28:17.370 --> 00:28:18.439
Happy New Year,
gentlemen.


348
00:28:23.370 --> 00:28:25.122
Is this
absolutely necessary?


349
00:28:25.210 --> 00:28:26.210
Yeah.

350
00:28:26.410 --> 00:28:27.506
(GUNSHOT)
(ANIMALS CLAMORING)


351
00:28:27.530 --> 00:28:30.169
Stop! What are you doing?

352
00:28:30.250 --> 00:28:31.386
These creatures
won't survive the winter.


353
00:28:31.410 --> 00:28:34.049
It's an order from high command.
There's nothing I can do.


354
00:28:34.530 --> 00:28:35.565
No, stop!

355
00:28:35.890 --> 00:28:36.890
(ADAM GROANING)

356
00:28:38.690 --> 00:28:41.762
Mama!
Mama, who's shooting?


357
00:28:41.850 --> 00:28:44.569
Mama, they're shooting!
Who's shooting?


358
00:28:46.410 --> 00:28:48.241
(SOBBING)

359
00:28:49.250 --> 00:28:50.729
Make it stop.

360
00:28:53.130 --> 00:28:55.485
(ANTONINA SOBBING)
(GUNSHOTS CONTINUE)


361
00:28:58.410 --> 00:28:59.729
(MEN LAUGHING)

362
00:29:02.290 --> 00:29:04.929
Tell me, where's the owner?
He's gone.


363
00:29:05.610 --> 00:29:07.490
Would you tell his wife
I'd like to talk to her?


364
00:29:08.130 --> 00:29:09.130
(GUNSHOT)
(ANIMAL GROANS)


365
00:29:10.570 --> 00:29:12.003
They left on holiday.

366
00:29:12.810 --> 00:29:14.368
(GUNSHOT)
(ANIMAL SCREECHES)


367
00:29:15.890 --> 00:29:18.404
I thought I saw her.
I must have been mistaken.


368
00:29:18.930 --> 00:29:19.930
(GUNSHOT)

369
00:29:22.770 --> 00:29:24.442
(SQUAWKING)

370
00:29:25.570 --> 00:29:28.038
(BULLETS RICOCHETING)

371
00:29:31.450 --> 00:29:32.450
(GUN COCKS)

372
00:29:35.810 --> 00:29:36.810
(GUNSHOT)

373
00:29:39.690 --> 00:29:41.965
Have it stuffed
and mounted.


374
00:29:50.330 --> 00:29:51.445
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

375
00:30:17.650 --> 00:30:19.368
Keep moving, children.

376
00:30:19.450 --> 00:30:22.089
Dr. Korczak.
That's right.


377
00:30:22.170 --> 00:30:23.728
Dr. Korczak?
Not too far now.


378
00:30:26.410 --> 00:30:27.809
Not too far now.

379
00:30:53.050 --> 00:30:54.930
SZYMON: They're forcing Jews
out of their homes,


380
00:30:54.970 --> 00:30:56.608
and they are taking us all
to the ghetto.


381
00:30:58.010 --> 00:31:00.763
They dragged Maurycy away
like he was a criminal.


382
00:31:02.010 --> 00:31:04.843
That brilliant, kind man,
like he was nothing.


383
00:31:06.890 --> 00:31:09.848
We're going to go where they
want us to go, that's all.


384
00:31:12.130 --> 00:31:14.166
And when the war
is over,


385
00:31:15.450 --> 00:31:17.759
we'll come home again.

386
00:31:22.490 --> 00:31:24.685
I've known you
since we were boys, Jan.


387
00:31:24.770 --> 00:31:28.001
Go on, Szymon.
What do you need from me?


388
00:31:28.530 --> 00:31:30.998
I'd like to keep my insect
collection here with you.


389
00:31:31.090 --> 00:31:33.001
I can't take it with me.

390
00:31:33.090 --> 00:31:35.809
I want it to be safe.
It's my life's work, you know that.


391
00:31:35.890 --> 00:31:40.327
Of course, Szymon, yes.
We can put it in the basement.


392
00:31:40.410 --> 00:31:43.880
It's dry there, like a dungeon.
And no one will find it.


393
00:31:46.770 --> 00:31:50.080
Thank you, Jan.
Thank you.


394
00:31:55.250 --> 00:31:57.320
ANTONINA: We have room.

395
00:31:58.370 --> 00:32:00.838
We have
the storeroom upstairs.


396
00:32:00.930 --> 00:32:03.444
We could hide Magda there.

397
00:32:07.250 --> 00:32:08.524
Antonina.

398
00:32:13.730 --> 00:32:16.528
This is a human being.

399
00:32:16.610 --> 00:32:18.646
This is a Jew
hiding in our house.


400
00:32:19.770 --> 00:32:22.568
We can't even give her
a glass of water.


401
00:32:22.650 --> 00:32:25.084
Do you understand that?
Mmm.


402
00:32:25.170 --> 00:32:28.082
We could be shot
for a glass of water.


403
00:32:36.370 --> 00:32:39.282
So, we just close our eyes
and let her go.


404
00:32:41.250 --> 00:32:43.684
Our dearest friend
in all the world.


405
00:32:46.970 --> 00:32:49.165
We would have to
be sure about this.


406
00:32:51.090 --> 00:32:53.558
Think carefully because...

407
00:32:56.810 --> 00:32:58.687
We'd have to be very sure.

408
00:33:06.810 --> 00:33:09.483
JAN: Absolutely no sound
during the morning.


409
00:33:09.850 --> 00:33:12.364
No sound,
do you understand me?


410
00:33:13.330 --> 00:33:15.798
The cook leaves at 1:00.
She'll sleep in the day.


411
00:33:19.090 --> 00:33:24.562
At midnight, the patrol leaves,
and then you can come out.


412
00:33:26.610 --> 00:33:28.248
How long can I stay?

413
00:33:29.490 --> 00:33:32.687
I have nowhere else to go.

414
00:33:32.770 --> 00:33:35.364
You'll stay
till it's over.


415
00:33:42.370 --> 00:33:43.370
JAN: It's done.

416
00:33:45.010 --> 00:33:49.003
They've moved all the Jews behind
walls in the Nalewki District.


417
00:33:50.130 --> 00:33:52.121
And they're bringing in
very little food.


418
00:33:52.210 --> 00:33:55.520
ANTONINA: Oh, my God.
And no wood, nothing for the cold.


419
00:33:59.010 --> 00:34:01.285
Have you heard
anything about Maurycy?


420
00:34:01.370 --> 00:34:04.806
He's practicing law from a storefront.
That's all I know.


421
00:34:04.890 --> 00:34:07.609
I can't get through
the gates, Magda.


422
00:34:08.050 --> 00:34:11.087
No one enters the ghetto
without a pass.


423
00:34:15.170 --> 00:34:17.684
Listen,

424
00:34:17.770 --> 00:34:19.965
there are
people I know,


425
00:34:20.050 --> 00:34:22.484
people trying to help.

426
00:34:22.570 --> 00:34:25.130
They have trucks,
they have guns.


427
00:34:25.210 --> 00:34:27.599
And they want to use the
zoo as a way station.


428
00:34:27.690 --> 00:34:29.123
What do you mean?

429
00:34:30.250 --> 00:34:33.640
A place to hide Jews,
until safe houses can be found for them.


430
00:34:35.050 --> 00:34:37.883
A friend is different,
one friend.


431
00:34:39.610 --> 00:34:43.523
But more than one? That's dangerous, Jan.
You said it yourself.


432
00:34:43.610 --> 00:34:47.398
They're starving,
Antonina.


433
00:34:47.490 --> 00:34:49.048
Two kilometers away.

434
00:34:49.730 --> 00:34:52.642
They are trapped and starving
like rats in a cellar.


435
00:34:57.770 --> 00:34:58.770
ANTONINA: How many?

436
00:35:00.290 --> 00:35:01.405
Impossible to say.

437
00:35:01.850 --> 00:35:03.363
And for how long?

438
00:35:03.450 --> 00:35:05.839
They'd be our guests
until we found them refuge.


439
00:35:13.930 --> 00:35:15.283
A human zoo.

440
00:35:18.930 --> 00:35:22.843
We have to keep the grounds in operation,
or we're lost.


441
00:35:22.930 --> 00:35:26.366
But whatever it is,
whatever we do,


442
00:35:26.450 --> 00:35:28.042
we have to hide it
in plain sight.


443
00:35:54.810 --> 00:35:57.005
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS
IN GERMAN)


444
00:36:11.850 --> 00:36:15.047
We understand the war office
is going to close our zoo.


445
00:36:15.170 --> 00:36:19.288
An unfortunate consequence
of the occupation. I'm really sorry.


446
00:36:19.730 --> 00:36:22.722
Well, of course we want
to save it if we can.


447
00:36:22.810 --> 00:36:25.529
We've spent many years
building it.


448
00:36:25.610 --> 00:36:26.963
I'm sure you understand.

449
00:36:27.050 --> 00:36:28.688
I do.

450
00:36:28.770 --> 00:36:30.647
What do you propose,
Frau Zabinska?


451
00:36:32.090 --> 00:36:33.921
A pig farm, Herr Heck.

452
00:36:35.170 --> 00:36:36.239
A pig farm?

453
00:36:37.530 --> 00:36:39.919
(LAUGHS)

454
00:36:41.410 --> 00:36:43.685
Is this a joke?
No.


455
00:36:43.810 --> 00:36:45.607
Your men are hungry.

456
00:36:45.730 --> 00:36:49.166
Your officers,
they need meat.


457
00:36:49.250 --> 00:36:52.242
Uh, we need to keep
the zoo in operation, Lutz.


458
00:36:52.330 --> 00:36:54.798
We'll raise pigs in the
pens to feed your men,


459
00:36:54.890 --> 00:36:57.563
and we will save our zoo.

460
00:37:00.770 --> 00:37:04.763
Pigs. Well, they're cheap to farm,
of course, but how would you feed them?


461
00:37:06.450 --> 00:37:08.918
We could collect garbage
from the ghetto.


462
00:37:09.050 --> 00:37:10.970
Of course, with your permission.
(LIGHTER CLICKS)


463
00:37:12.210 --> 00:37:14.565
I certainly see your point.

464
00:37:14.650 --> 00:37:17.084
Your zoo's been of value.
That's very true.


465
00:37:17.570 --> 00:37:21.404
Your bison was exquisite.
A perfect specimen, and a terrible loss.


466
00:37:23.290 --> 00:37:25.087
I've spoken of it
to Hermann Göring,


467
00:37:25.170 --> 00:37:27.365
and I'm happy to say
that he's agreed with me.


468
00:37:27.450 --> 00:37:29.725
I am to start a breeding
program this summer.


469
00:37:31.010 --> 00:37:32.443
You're going
to breed bison?


470
00:37:32.530 --> 00:37:37.729
No, that plan has
no scope, no ambition.


471
00:37:38.410 --> 00:37:42.961
No, I intend to breed
aurochsen from the bison.


472
00:37:44.370 --> 00:37:47.123
Aurochsen. But...

473
00:37:48.290 --> 00:37:49.290
(LAUGHS)

474
00:37:49.370 --> 00:37:52.840
But they have been extinct
for 300 years, Lutz.


475
00:37:52.930 --> 00:37:54.648
They're storybook
creatures now.


476
00:37:54.730 --> 00:37:57.927
That's exactly the point.
I intend to bring them back.


477
00:37:58.050 --> 00:37:59.244
That's not possible.

478
00:38:00.970 --> 00:38:02.369
(CLEARS THROAT)

479
00:38:03.450 --> 00:38:06.408
I didn't know that you thought
so little of me, Dr. Zabinski.


480
00:38:09.210 --> 00:38:11.360
I devoted my life
to the study of genetics,


481
00:38:11.450 --> 00:38:15.045
and I'm well practiced in the
study of animal breeding.


482
00:38:15.130 --> 00:38:16.802
I'm an expert
in that field.


483
00:38:16.890 --> 00:38:21.042
And I think I know
more than anyone.


484
00:38:21.130 --> 00:38:22.324
Even more than you.

485
00:38:27.490 --> 00:38:30.323
Herr Göring must
respect you very much.


486
00:38:30.770 --> 00:38:32.965
Oh, I believe he does, yes.

487
00:38:35.010 --> 00:38:37.968
Well... (CLEARS THROAT)
I think the pigs will work.


488
00:38:38.850 --> 00:38:40.078
(SIGHS IN RELIEF)

489
00:38:40.170 --> 00:38:42.923
I'm sure Göring will be
pleased with the idea.


490
00:38:43.010 --> 00:38:47.242
And what an irony, a trayf
farm fed by Jewish garbage.


491
00:38:47.330 --> 00:38:50.242
And right under
their noses. (LAUGHS)


492
00:38:52.330 --> 00:38:53.330
Cheers!

493
00:38:53.490 --> 00:38:55.082
(PIGS SQUEALING)

494
00:39:09.370 --> 00:39:10.962
(INDISTINCT CHATTER
IN GERMAN)


495
00:39:15.650 --> 00:39:17.561
Hello, Lutz.
What's this? Jan.


496
00:39:17.850 --> 00:39:20.205
Draw them into the pen,
and close the gate!


497
00:39:20.290 --> 00:39:22.645
But be careful,
he's in a temper.


498
00:39:22.770 --> 00:39:24.328
(BISON GRUNTING)

499
00:39:27.370 --> 00:39:28.849
You're breeding them here?

500
00:39:28.930 --> 00:39:30.130
They require
a natural habitat.


501
00:39:30.970 --> 00:39:33.290
We thought of your zoo,
but we had to fight the war office.


502
00:39:33.370 --> 00:39:35.122
And then you came
knocking on my door,


503
00:39:35.210 --> 00:39:36.438
as if you could
read my mind.


504
00:39:36.530 --> 00:39:38.441
You paved the way with pigs.

505
00:39:38.530 --> 00:39:40.088
(LUTZ HECK AND ANTONINA LAUGH)

506
00:39:40.170 --> 00:39:42.410
What a crack-brained idea,
and what splendid luck for us!


507
00:39:46.410 --> 00:39:48.605
I'll work with him.

508
00:39:50.610 --> 00:39:53.966
We can keep our eye on him
with the bison here.


509
00:39:57.410 --> 00:40:00.402
Well, he trusts you,
that's clear.


510
00:40:02.570 --> 00:40:05.368
You have a way with him.

511
00:40:07.330 --> 00:40:10.606
I don't know how
I can ask you to do this.


512
00:40:13.170 --> 00:40:14.523
Then don't ask me.

513
00:40:15.890 --> 00:40:19.166
I'm going to do it,
that's all.


514
00:40:25.850 --> 00:40:27.249
(SNORTING)

515
00:40:30.570 --> 00:40:32.322
(INDISTINCT CHATTER
IN GERMAN)


516
00:40:38.370 --> 00:40:41.248
The feed's ready for the pigs.
I have to go.


517
00:40:41.610 --> 00:40:42.804
See you later, darling.

518
00:40:57.810 --> 00:41:00.119
SOLDIER: Halt!

519
00:41:09.650 --> 00:41:11.447
(SOLDIER SPEAKING GERMAN)

520
00:41:13.730 --> 00:41:14.924
It's the pig farmer
of Warsaw.


521
00:41:19.810 --> 00:41:21.641
(ENGINE STARTS)

522
00:41:21.730 --> 00:41:22.799
Up! Up!

523
00:42:05.890 --> 00:42:06.890
(SPEAKS GERMAN)

524
00:42:37.330 --> 00:42:38.558
MAURYCY: This looks good.

525
00:42:41.530 --> 00:42:42.530
This is fine.

526
00:42:45.850 --> 00:42:46.850
Zabinski!

527
00:42:49.090 --> 00:42:50.205
Excuse me.

528
00:43:00.090 --> 00:43:03.526
It's pig meat.
Put it away.


529
00:43:08.090 --> 00:43:11.969
So, how is Magda?
Is she all right?


530
00:43:12.050 --> 00:43:15.486
Yes. She worries about you.

531
00:43:15.570 --> 00:43:17.606
What could I do?
I had no choice.


532
00:43:18.530 --> 00:43:20.839
You can't hide this face.
(CHUCKLES)


533
00:43:26.810 --> 00:43:30.120
Uh... It's...

534
00:43:30.210 --> 00:43:32.485
It's worse
than I realized.


535
00:43:33.770 --> 00:43:37.524
There's a young girl
back there.


536
00:43:37.610 --> 00:43:40.807
It's a... A child.

537
00:43:43.130 --> 00:43:44.802
And two soldiers
are with her.


538
00:43:44.970 --> 00:43:47.120
No one is safe.

539
00:43:49.050 --> 00:43:51.928
I don't know
what will happen now.


540
00:43:52.010 --> 00:43:55.764
What do they intend
to do with us, Jan?


541
00:43:57.970 --> 00:43:58.970
Thank you.

542
00:44:04.610 --> 00:44:06.680
(CHILDREN CHATTERING)

543
00:44:06.770 --> 00:44:07.964
Thank you.

544
00:44:12.130 --> 00:44:13.768
You must stop now,
children.


545
00:44:13.850 --> 00:44:17.001
We need the peelings
for our soup.


546
00:44:20.410 --> 00:44:23.322
Dr. Korczak. I'm sorry,
we have nothing else to eat.


547
00:44:23.410 --> 00:44:27.198
No, no, I should have realized.
Uh, may we speak privately?


548
00:44:27.330 --> 00:44:29.685
I might be able to help you.
Yes, of course.


549
00:44:30.490 --> 00:44:31.969
(INDISTINCT WHISPERING)

550
00:44:47.370 --> 00:44:50.487
It's pig meat.
I'll bring more when I can.


551
00:44:57.050 --> 00:44:58.050
I can get you out.

552
00:44:59.890 --> 00:45:03.678
People know your books.
They will take care of you.


553
00:45:03.810 --> 00:45:05.880
You should leave with me,
Dr. Korczak.


554
00:45:05.970 --> 00:45:10.122
But then what of
the children?


555
00:45:10.210 --> 00:45:12.440
What of them, Dr. Zabinski?

556
00:45:12.530 --> 00:45:14.725
My heart is
no different than yours.


557
00:45:15.370 --> 00:45:19.727
I should not be here,
they should not be here,


558
00:45:19.850 --> 00:45:22.967
you should not be here.

559
00:45:27.450 --> 00:45:29.042
(JAN WHISTLES)

560
00:45:39.450 --> 00:45:42.010
(WHISTLES)
Go, go, go.


561
00:45:53.890 --> 00:45:55.243
Cover yourself.

562
00:46:14.530 --> 00:46:16.730
(GASPS) I can help you. You
have to be very, very quiet.


563
00:46:17.130 --> 00:46:18.563
Very quiet.

564
00:46:19.690 --> 00:46:22.363
Here, go in, go, go.
(MOANING IN PROTEST)


565
00:46:22.450 --> 00:46:24.008
Stay down.

566
00:46:24.090 --> 00:46:25.648
Good girl.

567
00:46:27.810 --> 00:46:29.368
(GIRL GASPING)

568
00:46:35.130 --> 00:46:36.848
Move over.

569
00:46:40.410 --> 00:46:41.843
(ENGINE STARTS)

570
00:46:52.770 --> 00:46:54.169
SOLDIER: Halt!

571
00:46:57.450 --> 00:46:58.803
(SOLDIERS SPEAKING GERMAN)

572
00:47:23.530 --> 00:47:24.530
(BANGING ON DOOR)

573
00:47:47.050 --> 00:47:48.847
JAN: Stay in, but listen.

574
00:47:51.210 --> 00:47:52.768
We will show you
into a tunnel.


575
00:47:52.850 --> 00:47:54.210
And you will spend
the night there.


576
00:47:54.490 --> 00:47:56.799
The German patrol comes back
shortly after dawn.


577
00:47:56.890 --> 00:47:59.040
But you will be
woken before that


578
00:47:59.130 --> 00:48:00.358
and taken
outside of Warsaw.


579
00:48:01.610 --> 00:48:02.610
Understand?

580
00:48:03.050 --> 00:48:05.245
Go. Keep your heads down.

581
00:48:05.330 --> 00:48:08.481
Hurry. Through the tunnel.

582
00:48:08.570 --> 00:48:10.800
Through the tunnel.
Go through the tunnel.


583
00:48:18.050 --> 00:48:19.563
Hello.

584
00:48:20.410 --> 00:48:21.479
Hey.

585
00:48:26.250 --> 00:48:27.922
(BREATHING SHAKILY)

586
00:48:35.410 --> 00:48:36.843
(WHIMPERING)

587
00:48:47.930 --> 00:48:49.921
There's a cook
that comes every morning.


588
00:48:52.570 --> 00:48:54.686
Please, you can't
make a sound.


589
00:48:57.290 --> 00:48:58.359
(WHIMPERS SOFTLY)

590
00:49:02.330 --> 00:49:03.763
Will you tell me your name?

591
00:49:08.450 --> 00:49:10.441
Mine is Antonina.

592
00:49:13.450 --> 00:49:18.478
A new hiding place
can feel strange.


593
00:49:19.730 --> 00:49:23.803
But I promise you, you're
going to be all right.


594
00:49:26.290 --> 00:49:28.281
I'll stay with you
if you like.


595
00:49:40.250 --> 00:49:42.366
I'm right here.

596
00:49:53.850 --> 00:49:54.999
Now.

597
00:50:07.610 --> 00:50:08.725
Good work, Jan.

598
00:50:08.850 --> 00:50:11.444
The army's waiting for them in Lomza.
Good luck.


599
00:50:38.370 --> 00:50:41.487
If you tell me
your family name,


600
00:50:41.570 --> 00:50:43.686
we can look for them.

601
00:50:45.090 --> 00:50:47.320
Maybe we could
bring them here.


602
00:50:57.170 --> 00:51:00.526
What a terrible time
you must have had.


603
00:51:02.930 --> 00:51:03.930
(SNIFFLES)

604
00:51:08.890 --> 00:51:11.085
My father died.

605
00:51:14.930 --> 00:51:18.002
He was shot
in St. Petersburg.


606
00:51:23.090 --> 00:51:24.239
I was...

607
00:51:27.090 --> 00:51:29.650
Me, I was about your age.

608
00:51:36.530 --> 00:51:39.647
We were taken in
by friends sometimes,


609
00:51:43.250 --> 00:51:45.810
or by strangers.

610
00:51:50.730 --> 00:51:53.324
We were running
for so long.


611
00:51:54.570 --> 00:51:56.526
(SOBBING SOFTLY)

612
00:51:56.610 --> 00:52:01.365
And no one knows
how hard it is,


613
00:52:05.330 --> 00:52:07.764
a life in hiding.

614
00:52:12.650 --> 00:52:15.722
You can never tell
who your enemies are,


615
00:52:20.130 --> 00:52:21.529
or who to trust.

616
00:52:27.810 --> 00:52:31.644
Maybe that's why
I love animals so much.


617
00:52:37.090 --> 00:52:39.684
You look in their eyes,

618
00:52:41.330 --> 00:52:44.163
and you know exactly
what's in their hearts.


619
00:52:50.290 --> 00:52:51.848
They're not like people.

620
00:53:00.170 --> 00:53:01.842
We live in a zoo.

621
00:53:04.610 --> 00:53:05.725
That's where you are,

622
00:53:08.370 --> 00:53:10.884
in a zoo.

623
00:53:13.690 --> 00:53:17.000
Most of the animals are gone
now because of the bombing.


624
00:53:18.490 --> 00:53:20.128
But this one,

625
00:53:25.450 --> 00:53:27.645
she was left behind.

626
00:53:52.890 --> 00:53:53.925
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

627
00:54:32.970 --> 00:54:34.403
(COIN CLATTERS)

628
00:55:22.210 --> 00:55:23.210
JAN: (WHISPERING) Quiet.

629
00:55:41.090 --> 00:55:42.090
This way.

630
00:55:42.170 --> 00:55:44.764
Women and children will
stay here in the basement,


631
00:55:44.850 --> 00:55:47.762
until we can find a safe
house that can take you.


632
00:55:48.050 --> 00:55:49.324
We shall be
possums now.


633
00:55:49.810 --> 00:55:51.890
We shall sleep in the mornings
when the cook is here.


634
00:55:53.690 --> 00:55:55.328
I will play my piano
after midnight,


635
00:55:55.410 --> 00:55:57.480
and then you'll know
it's safe to come out.


636
00:55:57.850 --> 00:56:02.048
But if you hear the piano
in the day, you must hide.


637
00:56:08.050 --> 00:56:09.244
(PIANO PLAYING)

638
00:56:27.650 --> 00:56:28.969
(DOOR OPENS)

639
00:57:51.010 --> 00:57:52.762
(INDISTINCT CHATTER
IN GERMAN)


640
00:58:00.410 --> 00:58:01.638
It's so cold today.

641
00:58:03.410 --> 00:58:05.480
Would you please make
a double batch of soup?


642
00:58:08.450 --> 00:58:09.644
(KNIFE STRIKING)

643
00:58:37.290 --> 00:58:38.666
LUTZ HECK:
We'll mate them this summer.


644
00:58:38.690 --> 00:58:40.306
Mmm-hmm.
She'll be in estrus a short time.


645
00:58:40.330 --> 00:58:42.207
Yes, a day at most.
Exactly.


646
00:58:43.490 --> 00:58:45.287
(MUFFLED CONVERSATION)

647
00:58:56.210 --> 00:58:59.885
Well, I'm afraid I've worn
you out with all our talk.


648
00:59:00.010 --> 00:59:04.401
Oh, not at all.
I've enjoyed your company.


649
00:59:05.250 --> 00:59:06.250
Have you?

650
00:59:08.770 --> 00:59:09.970
Still, I think
it's time to go.


651
00:59:30.930 --> 00:59:31.930
(SOBBING)

652
00:59:33.610 --> 00:59:34.610
(SHUSHING)

653
00:59:34.690 --> 00:59:35.690
(MUFFLED WAILING)

654
00:59:36.410 --> 00:59:37.843
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

655
01:00:02.130 --> 01:00:03.768
Goodbye, Antonina.

656
01:00:17.090 --> 01:00:18.284
(FRONT DOOR OPENING)

657
01:00:20.090 --> 01:00:21.205
(FRONT DOOR CLOSING)

658
01:00:39.570 --> 01:00:41.606
(DOOR BELL DINGING)

659
01:00:57.130 --> 01:00:59.644
We haven't much time,
Mrs. Aszer.


660
01:00:59.730 --> 01:01:01.925
Your friends are
waiting for you in Lódz.


661
01:01:02.010 --> 01:01:03.568
Rys, please,
bring her upstairs.


662
01:01:16.490 --> 01:01:18.162
(SOLDIER SPEAKING GERMAN)

663
01:01:21.010 --> 01:01:24.400
Goodbye, cousin!
Visit us again soon!


664
01:02:05.730 --> 01:02:08.847
ANTONINA: I always
wanted to draw... (GASPS)


665
01:02:09.050 --> 01:02:10.768
...but I was
never good at it.


666
01:02:13.450 --> 01:02:16.647
I hope someday,
you'll teach me?


667
01:02:23.650 --> 01:02:25.402
Can we see your rabbit?

668
01:02:44.650 --> 01:02:45.924
What is his name?

669
01:02:52.530 --> 01:02:55.169
I call him Piotr.

670
01:02:57.730 --> 01:03:00.847
It was my brother's name.

671
01:03:02.450 --> 01:03:05.522
MEICIO:
And what's your name?


672
01:03:11.170 --> 01:03:15.243
They called me Urszula.

673
01:03:17.090 --> 01:03:18.648
Urszula means "she-bear."

674
01:03:23.290 --> 01:03:24.325
Did you know that?

675
01:03:30.810 --> 01:03:32.129
Yes.

676
01:03:40.330 --> 01:03:42.082
My father used to say it.

677
01:03:48.970 --> 01:03:50.528
(PIANO PLAYING)

678
01:04:09.690 --> 01:04:11.009
(INDISTINCT MURMURING)

679
01:04:13.410 --> 01:04:15.287
Good evening. Hello.

680
01:05:07.370 --> 01:05:08.723
It's almost
bearable today.


681
01:05:30.650 --> 01:05:31.924
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

682
01:05:51.770 --> 01:05:52.770
(CAR DOOR CLOSES)

683
01:05:57.890 --> 01:05:59.209
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

684
01:06:01.650 --> 01:06:02.969
Herr Heck, Miss.

685
01:06:04.450 --> 01:06:05.450
Oh.

686
01:06:06.370 --> 01:06:08.759
What a surprise.
I wasn't expecting you today.


687
01:06:08.850 --> 01:06:10.203
A good surprise,
I hope.


688
01:06:10.290 --> 01:06:12.804
Of course.
Always a good surprise.


689
01:06:12.890 --> 01:06:14.528
I have another
surprise for you.


690
01:06:14.610 --> 01:06:16.965
Our girl is ready. Come.

691
01:06:21.930 --> 01:06:23.648
(SNORTING AND GRUNTING)

692
01:06:25.970 --> 01:06:27.562
(MAN LAUGHS)

693
01:06:29.730 --> 01:06:32.688
Take the rope,
keep her calm.


694
01:06:33.250 --> 01:06:34.250
Steady.

695
01:06:39.130 --> 01:06:40.130
(LAUGHS)

696
01:06:41.610 --> 01:06:44.078
(SOLDIERS CHATTERING
AND LAUGHING)


697
01:06:44.170 --> 01:06:47.162
LUTZ HECK: Now, come on,
come on. Come on.


698
01:06:47.330 --> 01:06:48.649
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

699
01:06:48.770 --> 01:06:50.044
(BELLOWING)

700
01:06:53.130 --> 01:06:55.007
(SOLDIERS LAUGHING)
(LUTZ HECK GRUNTING)


701
01:06:56.690 --> 01:06:58.760
(BISON BELLOWS)
(GASPS)


702
01:07:00.890 --> 01:07:01.925
That's it.

703
01:07:02.010 --> 01:07:03.363
(SPEAKS GERMAN)
(TUTTING)


704
01:07:03.450 --> 01:07:05.202
(BELLOWING)

705
01:07:06.210 --> 01:07:07.210
LUTZ HECK: That's it.

706
01:07:10.490 --> 01:07:11.889
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

707
01:07:12.010 --> 01:07:13.648
That's it.

708
01:07:52.010 --> 01:07:54.570
Where are your shoes?

709
01:07:54.650 --> 01:07:57.005
I must have left them
in the pen.


710
01:07:57.090 --> 01:07:59.081
Well, put them on, please.
You're not a child.


711
01:08:06.930 --> 01:08:08.204
(BANGING ON DOOR)

712
01:08:10.050 --> 01:08:11.369
(WHISPERING)
Upstairs!


713
01:08:14.170 --> 01:08:16.604
(SHUSHING)
Go, go, go!


714
01:08:20.650 --> 01:08:22.208
(PLAYING PIANO LOUDLY)

715
01:08:32.250 --> 01:08:33.250
Yes?

716
01:08:33.290 --> 01:08:35.758
DR. ZIEGLER: Dr. Zabinski?
Yes.


717
01:08:35.850 --> 01:08:40.002
I'm Dr. Ziegler. I'm the director
of the Ghetto Labor Bureau.


718
01:08:42.450 --> 01:08:44.566
I've come to see the bugs.

719
01:08:46.810 --> 01:08:49.529
Szymon died, you see.

720
01:08:49.970 --> 01:08:53.360
Szymon and I went
hunting many times.


721
01:08:53.810 --> 01:08:57.519
I'm a bit of
a bug man myself.


722
01:08:57.610 --> 01:09:00.966
An amateur entomologist,
you might say.


723
01:09:05.690 --> 01:09:06.805
Wonderful.

724
01:09:08.490 --> 01:09:10.685
What an extraordinary
collection.


725
01:09:12.650 --> 01:09:14.561
Szymon died of an ulcer.

726
01:09:14.650 --> 01:09:18.768
It exploded in his stomach.
He couldn't be saved.


727
01:09:19.490 --> 01:09:21.685
It's such a tragedy
for me.


728
01:09:25.370 --> 01:09:27.679
I respected him
very much indeed.


729
01:09:33.210 --> 01:09:34.802
Uh...

730
01:09:34.890 --> 01:09:39.042
Szymon told me about you.

731
01:09:46.250 --> 01:09:47.444
He...

732
01:09:51.770 --> 01:09:53.840
...said some, um...

733
01:09:55.770 --> 01:09:57.362
...interesting things.

734
01:10:14.050 --> 01:10:15.050
Uh...

735
01:10:15.770 --> 01:10:17.089
Listen to me.

736
01:10:22.250 --> 01:10:26.562
The ghetto walls were built against
our Labor Bureau building.


737
01:10:28.170 --> 01:10:30.001
We have two doors.

738
01:10:30.090 --> 01:10:33.844
One opens into the
free side of the city,


739
01:10:33.930 --> 01:10:35.409
the other,
into the ghetto.


740
01:10:35.490 --> 01:10:39.449
In one way, out the other,
you understand me?


741
01:10:40.730 --> 01:10:41.730
Yes.

742
01:10:43.970 --> 01:10:48.805
I will give you papers that will
give you access either way.


743
01:10:49.810 --> 01:10:52.119
Dr. Zabinski,
welcome to the Labor Office.


744
01:10:52.210 --> 01:10:54.280
You can take the workers out,

745
01:10:54.370 --> 01:10:56.725
I will see that
they are signed back in.


746
01:10:56.850 --> 01:10:58.886
(TYPEWRITERS CLACKING)

747
01:10:59.010 --> 01:11:01.285
This is Dr. Zabinski.
He works for me.


748
01:11:01.370 --> 01:11:04.043
You will allow him through
whenever he comes or goes.


749
01:11:06.850 --> 01:11:11.640
Look, this is Dr. Zabinski,
he's allowed to pass through every time.


750
01:11:15.410 --> 01:11:17.526
(SOLDIERS CHATTERING
IN GERMAN)


751
01:11:18.690 --> 01:11:19.918
Open the gate!

752
01:11:23.450 --> 01:11:25.202
I look forward to
working with you.


753
01:11:30.450 --> 01:11:32.202
(CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKS)

754
01:11:32.730 --> 01:11:34.527
(SOLDIERS SHOUTING)
(GUNFIRE)


755
01:11:34.650 --> 01:11:35.924
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

756
01:11:43.610 --> 01:11:47.444
Bring them out.
Bring as many as you can.


757
01:12:07.770 --> 01:12:08.839
Go.

758
01:12:22.730 --> 01:12:23.765
Come.

759
01:12:42.210 --> 01:12:44.166
Thank you. Go.

760
01:12:48.770 --> 01:12:51.045
Right, right,
right, right.


761
01:13:06.490 --> 01:13:08.401
Watch out. Watch out.

762
01:13:08.570 --> 01:13:10.720
(SOLDIERS CHATTERING
IN GERMAN)


763
01:13:30.810 --> 01:13:32.926
Goodbye. See you soon.

764
01:13:54.530 --> 01:13:56.248
(SOLDIER SHOUTING)

765
01:13:58.570 --> 01:13:59.570
Who is this?

766
01:14:00.330 --> 01:14:03.128
What do you mean?
He works for me. I'm Dr. Jan Zabinski.


767
01:14:03.410 --> 01:14:06.925
Yes, but who is he?
I've never seen him before.


768
01:14:10.490 --> 01:14:13.687
He is Dr. Kleinhauser.

769
01:14:13.770 --> 01:14:15.283
He is with me.

770
01:14:15.370 --> 01:14:17.759
Do you want me to go
to the Labor Bureau?


771
01:14:17.850 --> 01:14:21.365
Do you want me to waste
Dr. Ziegler's time, his valuable time,


772
01:14:21.730 --> 01:14:24.369
to have him come all the way here,
to talk to you,


773
01:14:24.450 --> 01:14:26.645
to tell you
that he is with me?


774
01:14:27.850 --> 01:14:28.850
What do you want?

775
01:14:31.610 --> 01:14:33.043
I'm sorry, Dr. Zabinski.

776
01:14:36.650 --> 01:14:37.969
My apologies,
Dr. Kleinhauser.


777
01:14:42.810 --> 01:14:44.528
Just keep walking.

778
01:14:57.730 --> 01:14:59.527
Magda!

779
01:15:03.330 --> 01:15:04.330
(SOBBING)

780
01:15:19.210 --> 01:15:20.484
(PIANO PLAYING)

781
01:15:27.730 --> 01:15:29.561
You agree to have me here?

782
01:15:32.050 --> 01:15:33.768
You will be
in great danger.


783
01:15:46.890 --> 01:15:47.890
(WOMAN LAUGHS)

784
01:16:06.530 --> 01:16:07.565
Will you come to bed?

785
01:16:09.570 --> 01:16:10.685
I won't sleep.

786
01:16:13.290 --> 01:16:15.246
It's all right.

787
01:16:17.130 --> 01:16:19.246
Let's just lie together

788
01:16:21.770 --> 01:16:24.079
for a little while.

789
01:16:27.810 --> 01:16:29.448
Was he here today?

790
01:16:31.650 --> 01:16:32.650
Yes.

791
01:16:36.050 --> 01:16:40.168
The female's strong.
She'll give birth in spring.


792
01:16:42.090 --> 01:16:43.648
Did he...

793
01:16:43.730 --> 01:16:47.803
Did he bathe you, Punia?
Did he wash your hands?


794
01:16:50.930 --> 01:16:52.682
No.

795
01:16:52.770 --> 01:16:54.601
Jan.

796
01:16:56.250 --> 01:16:57.250
Jan.

797
01:16:58.970 --> 01:17:01.962
We were nearly
caught today.


798
01:17:20.970 --> 01:17:22.642
(ANTONINA SOBBING QUIETLY)

799
01:17:28.370 --> 01:17:32.158
Antonina? What is it?

800
01:17:32.690 --> 01:17:34.487
(SOBBING)
I'm sorry.


801
01:17:35.850 --> 01:17:40.002
Don't be silly.
What should you be sorry for?


802
01:17:43.050 --> 01:17:45.325
I want to do what's right.

803
01:17:47.570 --> 01:17:52.325
My heart is filled with it, my
stomach with such loathing.


804
01:17:55.650 --> 01:17:58.767
And I don't know
what to do.


805
01:17:58.850 --> 01:18:02.445
It's a new world, Antonina.

806
01:18:02.530 --> 01:18:05.442
Our lives are
turned upside down.


807
01:18:05.530 --> 01:18:07.646
How can any of us
know anything now?


808
01:18:10.730 --> 01:18:13.608
Miss, I can't find
any jars of beans, or...


809
01:18:17.290 --> 01:18:21.681
You must continue to use your ointment,
Mrs. Zabinska, for your hands.


810
01:18:21.770 --> 01:18:25.365
Just as I instructed.
Now, I will check your pulse.


811
01:18:26.170 --> 01:18:27.250
ANTONINA:
Thank you, Doctor.


812
01:18:28.490 --> 01:18:31.209
Pietrasia, do you mind?
No, no, no.


813
01:18:31.290 --> 01:18:34.362
I'm sorry, Doctor.
I didn't see you come in.


814
01:18:38.930 --> 01:18:40.363
(EXHALES DEEPLY)

815
01:18:41.330 --> 01:18:45.767
You know, we've had to let
most of the zookeepers go.


816
01:18:48.250 --> 01:18:49.524
Times are very hard.

817
01:18:51.250 --> 01:18:53.161
It's not your fault.

818
01:18:54.450 --> 01:18:58.602
You have always been so good to me, Miss.
You and your husband.


819
01:19:01.210 --> 01:19:04.088
Now, I'll be good to you.

820
01:19:07.890 --> 01:19:09.528
Be careful.

821
01:19:16.690 --> 01:19:17.759
(DOOR CLOSES)

822
01:19:20.210 --> 01:19:21.563
(RAIN PATTERING)

823
01:19:23.970 --> 01:19:26.530
MAN: (ON LOUDSPEAKER)
Attention. Attention.


824
01:19:26.610 --> 01:19:29.920
Tomorrow the evacuation
of the ghetto will begin.


825
01:19:31.490 --> 01:19:33.958
Pack your belongings,
and prepare for resettlement.


826
01:19:35.850 --> 01:19:37.966
(ANNOUNCEMENT
CONTINUES IN GERMAN)


827
01:19:46.850 --> 01:19:48.442
(SOLDIERS CHATTERING
IN GERMAN)


828
01:20:16.970 --> 01:20:21.168
And now,
listen to an old story.


829
01:20:21.250 --> 01:20:26.244
I wrote it for you.
It's a children's tale.


830
01:20:26.330 --> 01:20:28.002
So...
Dr. Korczak...


831
01:20:29.290 --> 01:20:30.330
Where are they taking you?

832
01:20:30.370 --> 01:20:34.488
We are going to
a land called Ro,


833
01:20:34.570 --> 01:20:36.845
to visit a great
magician there.


834
01:20:36.930 --> 01:20:41.720
His name is Zi.
He's a very good friend of mine.


835
01:20:41.810 --> 01:20:44.005
Yes.

836
01:20:44.090 --> 01:20:46.809
(QUIETLY) Dr. Korczak,
my car is outside the gate.


837
01:20:46.890 --> 01:20:50.724
It's just outside,
just there.


838
01:20:50.810 --> 01:20:53.563
It's impossible.

839
01:20:53.650 --> 01:20:58.644
I need your help now,
or the fear will be unmanageable.


840
01:21:41.170 --> 01:21:43.365
God bless you,
Dr. Zabinski.


841
01:21:43.450 --> 01:21:45.361
Goodbye for now.

842
01:21:51.970 --> 01:21:53.847
Pray for us.

843
01:22:02.770 --> 01:22:04.123
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS)

844
01:22:10.610 --> 01:22:11.884
(BISON CALF GRUNTING)

845
01:22:38.450 --> 01:22:39.450
What's this?

846
01:22:41.050 --> 01:22:42.324
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

847
01:22:44.250 --> 01:22:46.241
LUTZ HECK: Look who's
joined the party.


848
01:22:46.810 --> 01:22:48.129
The pig farmer of Warsaw.

849
01:22:50.330 --> 01:22:53.640
What will the pig farmer
do now, I wonder.


850
01:22:53.730 --> 01:22:56.244
JAN: Who knows, Herr Heck?

851
01:22:57.690 --> 01:23:00.488
A man might be surprised.

852
01:23:00.690 --> 01:23:04.126
He comes here
whenever he likes.


853
01:23:04.210 --> 01:23:07.202
He touches you
however he likes.


854
01:23:09.170 --> 01:23:14.085
What would you have me do?
I can't send him away.


855
01:23:14.170 --> 01:23:15.922
We have to work
with him, we agreed.


856
01:23:16.010 --> 01:23:17.841
It was the only way
to do this.


857
01:23:17.930 --> 01:23:21.161
I never agreed to this.
Never.


858
01:23:22.010 --> 01:23:23.079
To what?
This...


859
01:23:23.170 --> 01:23:25.638
This dance you do with him.

860
01:23:25.730 --> 01:23:29.040
This fun little
game you play.


861
01:23:29.130 --> 01:23:33.203
You don't even see it.
He frightens me.


862
01:23:34.530 --> 01:23:38.603
I am here with a house
full of desperate people,


863
01:23:38.690 --> 01:23:42.444
and he comes here
and he frightens me,


864
01:23:42.530 --> 01:23:44.805
and you're not here.

865
01:23:44.890 --> 01:23:47.324
And there's nothing
I can do. You're not here.


866
01:23:47.410 --> 01:23:50.880
People are dying, Antonina.

867
01:23:51.010 --> 01:23:55.208
Thousands of people
are dying.


868
01:23:55.290 --> 01:23:59.522
And you are here.
You stay hidden here, safe and sound.


869
01:23:59.610 --> 01:24:02.841
You don't know.
You don't know.


870
01:24:02.930 --> 01:24:06.161
Grandparents,
women, children.


871
01:24:06.250 --> 01:24:07.683
The littlest of children.

872
01:24:08.130 --> 01:24:11.088
And I'm trying to help them,
but they're dying in my hands.


873
01:24:11.810 --> 01:24:14.199
And you don't know.

874
01:24:15.050 --> 01:24:16.483
You don't know
what it's like.


875
01:24:21.210 --> 01:24:22.563
(EXHALING SHAKILY)

876
01:24:25.050 --> 01:24:28.520
And here you are,

877
01:24:28.610 --> 01:24:30.168
fooling with that man.

878
01:24:33.290 --> 01:24:34.769
(SIGHS)

879
01:24:34.850 --> 01:24:37.080
Jan, don't you see?

880
01:24:39.410 --> 01:24:40.410
He owns us.

881
01:24:44.410 --> 01:24:47.368
He owns us now.

882
01:24:55.610 --> 01:24:58.602
Antonina. Antonina.

883
01:25:02.010 --> 01:25:03.762
(ANTONINA BREATHING HEAVILY)

884
01:25:12.090 --> 01:25:14.479
Mrs. Anzelowna?
Yes?


885
01:25:14.570 --> 01:25:16.003
And your mother?

886
01:25:17.530 --> 01:25:21.000
Out. Come out. Out.

887
01:25:26.810 --> 01:25:31.281
Here, down on your knees.
On your knees.


888
01:25:31.970 --> 01:25:33.119
Down!
Down!


889
01:25:38.090 --> 01:25:39.090
(WOMAN SCREAMS)

890
01:25:44.890 --> 01:25:46.960
Was it her hair?

891
01:25:49.610 --> 01:25:51.805
Was it her hair color?

892
01:25:52.650 --> 01:25:53.765
Of course not.

893
01:25:57.250 --> 01:26:01.323
Someone at the boarding house
must have turned them in.


894
01:26:12.290 --> 01:26:13.928
(RADIO TUNING)

895
01:26:15.650 --> 01:26:19.768
BROADCASTER: (ON RADIO)
On this day, the 19th of April, 1943,


896
01:26:19.850 --> 01:26:22.489
on the eve of
Adolf Hitler's birthday,


897
01:26:22.570 --> 01:26:24.765
Reichsführer Heinrich
Himmler announced


898
01:26:24.850 --> 01:26:27.444
the final extermination
of the Warsaw Ghetto.


899
01:26:28.410 --> 01:26:30.719
Rise up, citizens of Warsaw.

900
01:26:30.810 --> 01:26:33.608
Join our brothers
and sisters in the fight.


901
01:26:33.690 --> 01:26:37.569
For on this day,
our ghetto will be liquidated.


902
01:26:37.650 --> 01:26:40.323
The Warsaw Ghetto
will be no more.


903
01:26:41.050 --> 01:26:45.680
Today is April the 19th.
Passover begins tonight.


904
01:26:47.330 --> 01:26:48.479
(RADIO TURNS OFF)

905
01:26:51.850 --> 01:26:54.728
May we have a Seder?

906
01:26:54.810 --> 01:26:57.165
Antonina?

907
01:27:00.290 --> 01:27:01.609
I know it by heart.

908
01:27:08.130 --> 01:27:10.849
It's snowing.

909
01:27:14.650 --> 01:27:17.528
What is it?

910
01:27:59.730 --> 01:28:00.730
Mama?

911
01:28:04.530 --> 01:28:07.283
They're burning the ghetto.

912
01:28:21.290 --> 01:28:23.201
(SOLDIERS SPEAKING GERMAN)

913
01:28:31.450 --> 01:28:32.678
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

914
01:28:37.170 --> 01:28:39.445
(SINGING IN HEBREW)

915
01:28:55.210 --> 01:28:56.928
(SOLDIERS SPEAKING GERMAN)

916
01:28:57.530 --> 01:28:59.088
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

917
01:28:59.170 --> 01:29:01.001
(ALL SINGING IN HEBREW)

918
01:29:02.770 --> 01:29:03.770
(SHOUTING)

919
01:29:07.130 --> 01:29:08.609
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

920
01:29:08.690 --> 01:29:10.169
(GLASS SHATTERING)

921
01:29:11.170 --> 01:29:13.081
(PRAYING IN HEBREW)

922
01:29:24.250 --> 01:29:25.603
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS)

923
01:29:38.890 --> 01:29:41.358
(URSZULA SINGING IN HEBREW)

924
01:30:25.170 --> 01:30:28.799
Here's cash and papers.
We'll move Mrs. Mayzel to Bramki.


925
01:30:28.890 --> 01:30:30.881
They're taking Mrs. Poznanska
to Foksal Street.


926
01:30:30.970 --> 01:30:33.484
Jan...
Yeah, good.


927
01:30:42.890 --> 01:30:44.323
How did you get here?

928
01:30:44.410 --> 01:30:45.763
I followed you.

929
01:30:46.970 --> 01:30:48.722
You never let me
go anywhere.


930
01:30:49.690 --> 01:30:50.725
Drive on.

931
01:30:52.690 --> 01:30:54.442
Let me go!
Be quiet.


932
01:31:07.210 --> 01:31:08.643
(DOOR SLAMS OPEN)

933
01:31:15.050 --> 01:31:16.483
(GAS CAN RATTLES)

934
01:31:42.010 --> 01:31:43.602
Burn it down.

935
01:32:13.010 --> 01:32:15.285
Where's your mother?

936
01:32:15.890 --> 01:32:18.199
She's at the doctor's.

937
01:32:18.330 --> 01:32:19.330
Mmm-hmm.

938
01:32:21.530 --> 01:32:24.363
And your father?

939
01:32:26.050 --> 01:32:28.405
He's in Zalesie, I think.

940
01:32:31.010 --> 01:32:32.045
Zalesie?

941
01:32:35.650 --> 01:32:36.719
I bet it's cold out there.

942
01:32:37.570 --> 01:32:39.720
How long has he been there?

943
01:32:41.130 --> 01:32:42.882
A week. I mean, a month.

944
01:32:43.130 --> 01:32:45.246
A month? That's a long time.

945
01:32:48.250 --> 01:32:50.161
I thought I just
saw him the other day.


946
01:32:52.410 --> 01:32:56.005
No, I told you.
He's in Zalesie.


947
01:33:01.690 --> 01:33:03.806
Well, I love Zalesie.

948
01:33:05.410 --> 01:33:08.208
I like to swim there, in the lake.
It's beautiful.


949
01:33:09.850 --> 01:33:12.922
I bet you wanted
to go swimming, too.


950
01:33:13.010 --> 01:33:15.888
And that's why you yelled at
your father on Zurawia Street.


951
01:33:15.970 --> 01:33:17.244
No.

952
01:33:17.330 --> 01:33:18.968
Then why did you yell?

953
01:33:19.050 --> 01:33:20.927
I wasn't supposed
to leave the zoo.


954
01:33:29.530 --> 01:33:33.523
I want to speak to your
mother and your father.


955
01:33:33.610 --> 01:33:34.884
Tell them I've come by.

956
01:33:35.210 --> 01:33:36.404
Yes.

957
01:33:36.730 --> 01:33:38.288
But Papa's in Zalesie.

958
01:33:38.730 --> 01:33:40.129
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

959
01:33:42.330 --> 01:33:43.365
I forgot.

960
01:33:44.850 --> 01:33:46.806
Your papa's in Zalesie.

961
01:33:58.250 --> 01:34:01.242
Good boy for reminding me.

962
01:34:07.650 --> 01:34:09.402
Your parents
must be proud of you.


963
01:34:10.570 --> 01:34:12.925
Tell them they should
be proud of you.


964
01:34:16.210 --> 01:34:19.441
Heil Hitler.
Heil Hitler.


965
01:34:42.290 --> 01:34:43.564
Hitler ist kaputt!

966
01:34:44.450 --> 01:34:45.450
(SPEAKS GERMAN)

967
01:34:56.210 --> 01:34:57.802
Stand down.

968
01:34:58.810 --> 01:35:00.209
(ENGINE STARTS)

969
01:35:13.090 --> 01:35:14.364
(SOBBING QUIETLY)

970
01:35:36.610 --> 01:35:37.610
(GROANS)

971
01:35:45.050 --> 01:35:46.050
(EXHALES)

972
01:35:49.570 --> 01:35:50.685
(GROANING)

973
01:35:51.250 --> 01:35:52.319
(PANCHO CHITTERING)

974
01:35:54.810 --> 01:35:55.810
(COOS)

975
01:36:15.370 --> 01:36:17.361
We had a girl, Papa.

976
01:36:17.450 --> 01:36:20.089
I've named her Teresa,
like the saint.


977
01:36:22.250 --> 01:36:25.959
(STAMMERING) Oh, that's a good name.
That's a beautiful name.


978
01:36:28.410 --> 01:36:30.128
Hello, Teresa.

979
01:36:30.530 --> 01:36:31.758
(TERESA COOING)

980
01:36:34.290 --> 01:36:36.406
Are you all right?
Yes.


981
01:36:39.610 --> 01:36:41.646
I'm wonderful.

982
01:36:42.930 --> 01:36:45.506
BROADCASTER: (ON RADIO) This is Warsaw calling.
This is Warsaw calling.


983
01:36:45.530 --> 01:36:46.565
(GUNFIRE)

984
01:36:46.650 --> 01:36:49.722
August 1st, 1944.

985
01:36:49.810 --> 01:36:51.766
This is Warsaw calling.

986
01:36:52.330 --> 01:36:56.289
The Polish Home Army is rising
up against the Nazi Reich.


987
01:36:56.650 --> 01:37:00.199
We call on all
great citizens of Warsaw


988
01:37:00.290 --> 01:37:03.999
to free our city
and our nation.


989
01:37:04.090 --> 01:37:05.842
The German Army
must not stand.


990
01:37:05.970 --> 01:37:07.039
Follow me.

991
01:37:07.130 --> 01:37:10.281
This is Warsaw calling.
This is Warsaw calling.


992
01:37:10.370 --> 01:37:12.247
(EXPLOSIONS IN THE DISTANCE)

993
01:37:12.530 --> 01:37:14.168
Go!

994
01:37:29.010 --> 01:37:30.010
(SCREAMING)

995
01:37:36.330 --> 01:37:38.161
JAN: Aim.

996
01:37:38.690 --> 01:37:40.123
Shoot.

997
01:37:40.770 --> 01:37:41.770
(GROANS)

998
01:37:48.250 --> 01:37:49.285
Go.

999
01:37:51.490 --> 01:37:53.003
Go, go, go!

1000
01:37:58.570 --> 01:37:59.570
(GROANS)

1001
01:38:11.210 --> 01:38:13.485
I was told that
he was shot in the neck.


1002
01:38:13.570 --> 01:38:16.130
The Germans took him
to a prison camp,


1003
01:38:16.250 --> 01:38:17.649
but no one knows
where he is.


1004
01:38:18.050 --> 01:38:19.881
(SOBBING)

1005
01:38:24.250 --> 01:38:25.524
I'm sorry, Miss.

1006
01:38:27.250 --> 01:38:28.250
(ANTONINA SOBS)

1007
01:38:31.250 --> 01:38:35.084
BROADCASTER: (ON RADIO) This is Warsaw calling.
This is Warsaw calling.


1008
01:38:36.050 --> 01:38:40.566
Citizens of Warsaw,
we urge you to leave at once.


1009
01:38:40.690 --> 01:38:43.363
The city is no longer
safe for you.


1010
01:38:43.450 --> 01:38:46.840
I repeat, you are not safe.

1011
01:38:46.930 --> 01:38:50.161
We urge you to take
only what you can carry.


1012
01:38:50.250 --> 01:38:52.161
Leave at once.

1013
01:38:52.250 --> 01:38:54.844
This is Warsaw calling.

1014
01:38:54.930 --> 01:38:57.808
The Home Army is overrun.

1015
01:38:57.890 --> 01:38:59.846
The Russian offensive
has begun,


1016
01:38:59.930 --> 01:39:02.649
and the German Army
is expected to fall.


1017
01:39:03.610 --> 01:39:07.285
You are not safe.
This is Warsaw calling...


1018
01:39:14.450 --> 01:39:16.327
Herr Heck's taking
the bison out of Warsaw.


1019
01:39:18.810 --> 01:39:22.086
Miss, you're not
leaving the zoo.


1020
01:39:22.170 --> 01:39:24.730
I have to know
what happened to Jan.


1021
01:39:24.810 --> 01:39:26.801
Miss...
I have to know.


1022
01:39:34.010 --> 01:39:35.284
(SOLDIERS SHOUTING
INDISTINCTLY)


1023
01:40:25.210 --> 01:40:26.404
You've packed your things.

1024
01:40:27.850 --> 01:40:31.479
The war's turning.
I've been ordered back to Berlin.


1025
01:40:35.370 --> 01:40:37.361
What bad luck for us.

1026
01:40:39.690 --> 01:40:41.123
We'll be sorry to see you go.

1027
01:40:47.210 --> 01:40:50.964
I'm here to ask you,
my friend,


1028
01:40:51.050 --> 01:40:52.688
I'm looking for my husband.

1029
01:40:55.010 --> 01:40:56.887
He was captured
by German troops.


1030
01:40:57.450 --> 01:40:58.769
He was taken from the zoo?

1031
01:40:59.050 --> 01:41:00.449
No. From Old Town.

1032
01:41:00.530 --> 01:41:02.486
The underground army's
fighting in the Old Town.


1033
01:41:02.570 --> 01:41:03.969
What was Jan doing there?

1034
01:41:04.050 --> 01:41:05.529
Buying grass for the bison.

1035
01:41:08.930 --> 01:41:09.930
What did you say?

1036
01:41:11.250 --> 01:41:13.605
Jan was buying grass
and he was captured.


1037
01:41:19.530 --> 01:41:20.530
(CHUCKLES)

1038
01:41:23.530 --> 01:41:25.122
Why are you really here,
Antonina?


1039
01:41:27.090 --> 01:41:29.524
(VOICE BREAKING) I hoped you
might help me find him.


1040
01:41:31.410 --> 01:41:33.605
As a gift
to our friendship.


1041
01:41:35.810 --> 01:41:37.846
He might be dead.

1042
01:41:38.690 --> 01:41:40.601
He might be.
(CLEARS THROAT)


1043
01:41:42.770 --> 01:41:44.362
I don't know.
I don't know anything.


1044
01:41:49.930 --> 01:41:51.841
And what gift would
I receive in return?


1045
01:41:52.610 --> 01:41:54.566
I'm curious to know.

1046
01:42:44.170 --> 01:42:46.559
Has Jan been keeping
secrets from me?


1047
01:42:47.850 --> 01:42:49.044
No, of course not.

1048
01:42:49.690 --> 01:42:51.009
Are you lying to me,
Antonina?


1049
01:42:52.690 --> 01:42:53.725
No.

1050
01:42:55.610 --> 01:42:59.398
I just want to find what
happened to my husband.


1051
01:42:59.530 --> 01:43:01.600
And if he's dead,
I want to bury him.


1052
01:43:01.730 --> 01:43:04.847
"Hitler ist kaputt!"
I heard your son say it.


1053
01:43:05.170 --> 01:43:08.082
He's a child, Lutz.

1054
01:43:08.170 --> 01:43:10.479
It means nothing
to him, it's a game.


1055
01:43:10.570 --> 01:43:12.306
He hears things and he repeats them,
that's all...


1056
01:43:12.330 --> 01:43:13.365
Where does he hear them?

1057
01:43:14.970 --> 01:43:15.970
Um...

1058
01:43:16.850 --> 01:43:18.727
(STAMMERING)
I don't know.


1059
01:43:18.850 --> 01:43:20.970
People come and go all the time...
Who comes and goes?


1060
01:43:22.490 --> 01:43:25.721
(SOBBING) Soldiers
and guards and...


1061
01:43:25.850 --> 01:43:27.920
Believe me,
it means nothing to him.


1062
01:43:28.010 --> 01:43:29.346
Did he hear it from his father?
Did he?


1063
01:43:29.370 --> 01:43:30.644
No.

1064
01:43:32.770 --> 01:43:33.770
No.

1065
01:43:44.570 --> 01:43:46.128
You're lying to me,
Antonina.


1066
01:43:46.210 --> 01:43:47.643
I can see it
in your eyes.


1067
01:43:47.730 --> 01:43:48.958
No.

1068
01:43:49.050 --> 01:43:50.483
(GRUNTING)

1069
01:43:56.690 --> 01:43:58.521
No!

1070
01:43:59.050 --> 01:44:03.009
No, Lutz! No!

1071
01:44:05.410 --> 01:44:06.684
(GRUNTING)

1072
01:44:10.370 --> 01:44:11.598
(ANTONINA PANTING)

1073
01:44:15.330 --> 01:44:16.922
Look at me.

1074
01:44:19.250 --> 01:44:21.002
Look at me.

1075
01:44:26.930 --> 01:44:29.205
You disgust me.

1076
01:44:50.210 --> 01:44:52.599
So, that's how it is.

1077
01:44:54.530 --> 01:44:57.283
You hid it well.

1078
01:45:07.730 --> 01:45:09.960
But I wonder

1079
01:45:11.770 --> 01:45:13.681
what else have you
been hiding from me?


1080
01:45:15.130 --> 01:45:17.690
What have you been
up to, Frau Zabinska,


1081
01:45:18.450 --> 01:45:19.519
in your little zoo?

1082
01:45:22.290 --> 01:45:23.290
(GULPS)

1083
01:45:32.690 --> 01:45:34.169
(TELEPHONE RECEIVER RATTLES)

1084
01:45:34.770 --> 01:45:36.089
(DIALING)

1085
01:45:42.170 --> 01:45:43.170
(PANTING)

1086
01:45:44.610 --> 01:45:46.680
Excuse me, please!

1087
01:45:49.650 --> 01:45:50.650
ANTONINA: Jerzyk!

1088
01:45:54.170 --> 01:45:58.083
We have to get them out.
Herr Heck is coming.


1089
01:45:58.890 --> 01:46:00.323
The bombing is coming in.

1090
01:46:00.650 --> 01:46:02.481
(SPEAKING GERMAN)
Herr Heck wants you out.


1091
01:46:03.010 --> 01:46:04.728
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

1092
01:46:19.210 --> 01:46:20.848
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)
(SPEAKING POLISH)


1093
01:46:20.930 --> 01:46:21.930
ANTONINA: Everyone!

1094
01:46:23.730 --> 01:46:27.040
Pack your things. They're coming!
Hurry, they're coming!


1095
01:46:27.370 --> 01:46:30.726
Go! Go!

1096
01:46:31.930 --> 01:46:33.363
(CHATTERING IN POLISH)

1097
01:46:51.570 --> 01:46:52.639
Go to the truck.

1098
01:46:52.730 --> 01:46:54.322
Yeah, go quickly.
Go to the truck.


1099
01:46:54.770 --> 01:46:56.567
Quickly, please, go.
You must hurry!


1100
01:46:59.170 --> 01:47:00.364
Go. Go.

1101
01:47:08.610 --> 01:47:10.441
Come back when the war's over,
promise me.


1102
01:47:11.210 --> 01:47:13.883
She's coming with us!
Go quickly, boys!


1103
01:47:14.050 --> 01:47:15.688
Rys, get in the truck.
No, I'm not going.


1104
01:47:15.770 --> 01:47:18.284
Rys!
No!


1105
01:47:19.410 --> 01:47:21.366
Take Teresa,
we'll catch up to you.


1106
01:47:22.770 --> 01:47:23.919
Promise me you'll hurry.

1107
01:47:24.010 --> 01:47:25.762
Yes, please, go!
I'll find you, quick!


1108
01:47:34.610 --> 01:47:36.043
(HORNS HONKING)

1109
01:47:43.930 --> 01:47:46.808
Go downstairs, hide.
Don't make a sound.


1110
01:47:49.930 --> 01:47:51.158
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

1111
01:48:01.330 --> 01:48:03.560
Search the grounds.

1112
01:48:03.650 --> 01:48:04.690
(SOLDIERS SPEAKING GERMAN)

1113
01:48:06.010 --> 01:48:07.284
(GRUNTS SOFTLY)

1114
01:48:33.850 --> 01:48:35.078
(GRUNTING)

1115
01:49:28.370 --> 01:49:29.803
(GRUNTING)

1116
01:49:57.050 --> 01:49:58.529
(GRUNTING)

1117
01:50:54.170 --> 01:50:55.285
(DISTANT RUSTLING)

1118
01:50:57.170 --> 01:50:59.320
Hey!

1119
01:50:59.410 --> 01:51:00.604
(PANTING)

1120
01:51:09.210 --> 01:51:10.210
Stop!

1121
01:51:21.570 --> 01:51:24.448
Stop!
ANTONINA: Lutz.


1122
01:51:25.370 --> 01:51:26.849
Drop your weapon!

1123
01:51:27.650 --> 01:51:29.242
I said,
drop your weapon now.


1124
01:51:29.410 --> 01:51:30.525
Please.

1125
01:51:33.250 --> 01:51:36.128
Don't.

1126
01:51:36.210 --> 01:51:38.644
How many?

1127
01:51:38.850 --> 01:51:41.683
How many did you hide?

1128
01:51:43.290 --> 01:51:44.689
I don't know the number.

1129
01:51:48.370 --> 01:51:49.370
(ANTONINA SHOUTS)

1130
01:51:49.770 --> 01:51:52.443
Lock her in.
Lock her in!


1131
01:51:55.530 --> 01:51:57.088
ANTONINA: Do it, Rys.

1132
01:51:58.810 --> 01:52:02.246
Do what he says.
Do exactly what he says.


1133
01:52:05.050 --> 01:52:07.359
(YELLING) Come on!
(ANTONINA AND RYS GASP)


1134
01:52:07.450 --> 01:52:11.045
What kind of man shoots
an innocent child?


1135
01:52:11.130 --> 01:52:12.506
You have no idea
what kind of man I am.


1136
01:52:12.530 --> 01:52:13.565
Oh, but I do.

1137
01:52:14.290 --> 01:52:15.689
I do, Lutz.

1138
01:52:15.890 --> 01:52:18.848
You are a serious man.

1139
01:52:18.930 --> 01:52:22.639
You're a man of intelligence
and of breeding.


1140
01:52:23.450 --> 01:52:26.681
(VOICE BREAKING) Not the kind of
man that would shoot a child.


1141
01:52:26.770 --> 01:52:28.249
Mama!

1142
01:52:28.330 --> 01:52:31.561
No, Lutz! No!

1143
01:52:33.370 --> 01:52:34.928
(GUN FIRES)
Ah! No!


1144
01:52:43.610 --> 01:52:45.760
(WEEPING)

1145
01:52:48.050 --> 01:52:49.768
Rys.

1146
01:53:07.930 --> 01:53:08.930
Mama.

1147
01:53:13.290 --> 01:53:17.078
Mama.
Don't cry, Mama.


1148
01:53:18.770 --> 01:53:19.805
Don't cry.

1149
01:53:21.650 --> 01:53:22.650
I'm here.

1150
01:53:24.770 --> 01:53:26.362
I'm here.

1151
01:53:28.530 --> 01:53:32.443
I don't think I can walk.
Can you help me, sweetheart?


1152
01:53:38.570 --> 01:53:39.570
(ENGINE STARTS)

1153
01:54:41.330 --> 01:54:42.729
(CLICKING TONGUE)

1154
01:54:52.610 --> 01:54:53.610
(LOWING)

1155
01:56:03.970 --> 01:56:05.767
(BELLS TOLLING IN DISTANCE)

1156
01:56:34.010 --> 01:56:36.319
Hey!
RYS: Jerzyk!


1157
01:56:39.690 --> 01:56:40.918
Hey.

1158
01:56:41.010 --> 01:56:42.159
You're here.

1159
01:56:45.010 --> 01:56:48.161
It's my home, son, hmm?
Where else would I go?


1160
01:56:52.690 --> 01:56:53.690
(ANTONINA SNIFFLES)

1161
01:56:54.370 --> 01:56:55.849
You're home, hmm?

1162
01:58:23.610 --> 01:58:25.202
ANTONINA: Rys, look.

1163
01:58:26.610 --> 01:58:29.841
Look.
It's a strawberry.


1164
01:58:40.690 --> 01:58:43.045
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

1165
01:59:22.690 --> 01:59:23.690
(GASPS)

1166
01:59:24.770 --> 01:59:26.647
Jan!

1167
01:59:27.010 --> 01:59:28.966
Jan! (SOBBING)

1168
01:59:34.930 --> 01:59:35.930
(SOBBING)